It seems the ability's execution and movement are being processed in parallel. If the `TryToMoveToTarget()` function does not stop the ability execution, it will continue and perform the ability simultaneously while moving.

To resolve this issue, you can add a flag to indicate whether the character is currently moving to the target position. Set this flag to `true` inside the `TryToMoveToTarget()` function and add a callback function that sets it back to `false` when the destination is reached. Modify the ability execution to check this flag and ensure the ability is only triggered when the character is not moving.

Here's the modified code snippet:

```cpp
// Add an IsMovingToTarget variable in the Character class
bool IsMovingToTarget = false;

void TryToMoveToTarget(/* ... */)
{
    // ...
    // Set IsMovingToTarget to true as the character starts moving
    IsMovingToTarget = true;
} 

// Add a callback function that is called when the character reaches the destination
void OnDestinationReached()
{
    IsMovingToTarget = false;
    // Perform any other actions needed when the character reaches the destination (e.g., trigger the ability, reset timers, etc.)
}

// Modify your ability execution function
void ExecuteAbility(/* ... */)
{
    // ...

    if (!IsAvatarWithinRangeOfTarget)
    {
            // ...

            // Do not continue executing the ability if the character is still moving towards the target
            if (IsMovingToTarget)
            {
                return;
            }

            // If the character is not moving and still not within range, you can decide how to handle this (e.g., recall TryToMoveToTarget or just end the ability)
    }

    // Trigger the ability if within range and not moving
}
```

Make sure to set the `IsMovingToTarget` flag back to `false` after the character completes moving to the target location, preventing the ability from triggering while moving. Update the ability triggering check to consider this flag.

`UAbilityTask_MoveToLocation` is an AbilityTask designed to move an AI-controlled character to a target location within a gameplay ability. You can use this AbilityTask to simplify the movement logic in your ability. Here's how to use UAbilityTask_MoveToLocation in both C++ and Blueprints:

**C++**:

1. In your custom GameplayAbility class, include the AbilityTask header:

```cpp
#include "Abilities/Tasks/AbilityTask_MoveToLocation.h"
```

2. Create and start an `UAbilityTask_MoveToLocation` instance in your ability's activation function, for example, `ActivateAbility`:

```cpp
void UMyGameplayAbility::ActivateAbility(FGameplayAbilityActivateInfo SpecHandle, const FGameplayAbilityActorInfo& ActorInfo, const FGameplayAbilityActivationInfo& ActivationInfo, const FGameplayEventData* TriggerEventData, const FGameplayTag Tag)
{
    FVector TargetLocation; // Define your target location

    UAbilityTask_MoveToLocation* MoveTask = UAbilityTask_MoveToLocation::MoveToLocation(this, FName("MoveToLocation"), TargetLocation);

    if (MoveTask)
    {
        // Bind a function to be called when the character reaches the target location
        MoveTask->OnTargetReached.AddDynamic(this, &UMyGameplayAbility::OnTargetReached);

        // Activate the AbilityTask
        MoveTask->ReadyForActivation();
    }
}

void UMyGameplayAbility::OnTargetReached()
{
    // Handle logic to be executed when the character reaches the target location, such as triggering the ability or updating any flags.
}
```

**Blueprints**:

1. In your custom GameplayAbility blueprint, create a new "Move to Location" ability task node (make sure your Ability is set to `Instanced Per Execution`).

2. Connect this node to your ability activation logic and set the `Target Location` input to the location you want the character to move to.

3. Bind the "On Target Reached" event to a custom event in your blueprint. This custom event will handle the logic to be executed when the character reaches the target location.

Using `UAbilityTask_MoveToLocation` should simplify your movement handling code and integrate better with the GAS framework. Remember that this AbilityTask is designed to work with AI-controlled characters, so it might not work as intended for player-controlled characters.

When you want to move player-controlled characters to an ability's attack range before casting it, you can follow these steps to achieve this in both C++ and Blueprints. This implementation assumes you have set up an input binding to trigger the ability.

**C++**:

1. In your custom PlayerController class, create a function that moves your character to the target location based on the attack range offset.

```cpp
void AMyPlayerController::MoveToAbilityRange(FVector TargetLocation, float AttackRange)
{
    APawn* ControlledPawn = GetPawn();

    if (ControlledPawn)
    {
        FVector PawnLocation = ControlledPawn->GetActorLocation();
        FVector Direction = (TargetLocation - PawnLocation).GetSafeNormal();
        FVector Destination = TargetLocation - (Direction * AttackRange);

        UNavigationSystemV1* NavSystem = FNavigationSystem::GetCurrent<UNavigationSystemV1>(GetWorld());

        if (NavSystem)
        {
            FNavLocation ValidDestination;
            if (NavSystem->ProjectPointToNavigation(Destination, ValidDestination))
            {
                SimpleMoveToLocation(ValidDestination.Location);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

2. Trigger the `MoveToAbilityRange()` function when receiving the appropriate input from the player for the ability.

```cpp
void AMyPlayerController::SetupInputComponent()
{
    //... 

    InputComponent->BindAction("CastAbility", IE_Pressed, this, &AMyPlayerController::OnCastAbilityPressed);
}

void AMyPlayerController::OnCastAbilityPressed()
{
    // Retrieve target location and attack range based on your game logic here
    FVector TargetLocation;
    float AttackRange;

    MoveToAbilityRange(TargetLocation, AttackRange);

    // You can add a check here to see if the character is already in the attack range, and if so, cast the ability directly.
}
```

**Blueprints**:

1. In your custom PlayerController blueprint, create a function called `MoveToAbilityRange` that takes `TargetLocation` and `AttackRange` as input parameters.

2. Calculate the direction vector and final destination offset by the attack range, similar to the C++ example above.

3. Use the A* grid pathfinder to find a path to the destination point and move the player's character along that path. Use `SimpleMoveToLocation` of PlayerController or use CharacterMovementComponent (generally used for more complex pathfinding functionality)

4. In your input bindings, bind an action event (e.g., `CastAbility`) that calls the `MoveToAbilityRange` function with the target location and attack range.

5. Add a check within the input event to see if the character is already in the attack range; if so, cast the ability directly.

Using this method, you can move player-controlled characters to the desired location based on the attack range and then cast the ability upon reaching the target location.

